PART 3 — Harden the idempotency check itself
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Regardless of what part 1 finds, the check-then-act pattern in
EtsyReceiptWorker/PODFulfillmentService has a genuine race window
under concurrent processing (confirmed by the real IntegrityErrors in
the stress test log). Fix this properly:

1. Wrap the FulfillmentRecord insert in a try/except catching the
   specific IntegrityError on the (etsy_receipt_id, etsy_transaction_id)
   unique constraint.
2. On catching it, treat this as "another concurrent process already
   handled this receipt+transaction" — log it at debug/info level (not
   as a failure), roll back the session cleanly, and move on WITHOUT
   calling AlertService (this is expected behavior under concurrency,
   not an actionable error).
3. Confirm the session is properly rolled back after a caught
   IntegrityError before the worker's next iteration reuses it — verify
   this explicitly with a test, since a dirty session after a caught
   exception is a common source of follow-on bugs in SQLAlchemy.

